<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 10:3<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If66465f16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I6059a720933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Remand</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94fa0512e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:3.</label.designator><headtext>Scope of remand power</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel&apos;s remand power, like its transfer power, is somewhat limited. <eos/><bos/>The remand power is essentially the way the Panel “undoes” what it does when it orders transfer—return the cases still pending to the districts where they were pending when the Panel transferred them. <eos/><bos/>The Panel can only order remand of actions before it to the district in which they were pending at the time of transfer. <eos/><bos/>Thus, the Panel cannot “remand” actions to a different district.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If6648d006b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Similarly, the Panel cannot use the remand power to overrule a decision by either a transferee court or transferor court to transfer an action for all purposes under <cite.query w-src-number="0304914133" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1404" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I6fc1d8706b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">28 U.S.C.A. § 1404(a)</cite.query>.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If6648d016b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If66465f16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If6648d006b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext> <ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914133" w-serial-number="1977126499" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="933" ID="I6fc163416b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Air Crash Disaster in Ionian Sea on September 8, 1974, 438 F. Supp. 932, 933 (J.P.M.L. 1977)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914133" w-serial-number="1976142595" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="797" ID="I6fc163436b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Delta Airlines, Inc., Flight Attendant Weight Standards Litigation, 411 F. Supp. 795, 797 (J.P.M.L. 1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If6648d016b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914133" w-serial-number="1976142595" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="797" ID="I6fc1ff816b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Delta Airlines, Inc., Flight Attendant Weight Standards Litigation, 411 F. Supp. 795, 797 (J.P.M.L. 1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 10:3<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
